commit.message: Simplify logic in pdf14_initialize_ctx.

Remove n_chan member from pdf14_ctx_s.

We set it, but never use it, so just remove it.

Simplify calls to pdf14_initialize_ctx.

If we're passing 'dev' as the first argument, there is
nothing to be gained by always passing the same things derived
from dev as the second and third params. Let the function
derive them itself.
Squash warning seen on Windows builds.

Coverity 379260: Add more bounds checks for CIDFont strings

When building the CIDFont fallback file name/path from the various sources.

Rejig tags slightly.

We have a device structure member, graphics_type_tag, that we use to
hold the current tag. We use a bit in this indicate that the device
actually uses tags at all. This bit is never actually written to the
tags plane.

Given we only ever use 8 or 16 bits for the tag plane, why do we then
waste a bit using one of those for GS_DEVICE_ENCODES_TAGS ?

Here, we move GS_DEVICE_ENCODES_TAGS up to the 31st bit. This frees
another bit lower down for use with real tag values.

Also, we introduce an inline function, device_current_tag, to extract
the current tag. By using this, together with the existing function,
device_encodes_tags, we can restrict the use of GS_DEVICE_ENCODES_TAGS
within the broader code.

Devices - use proper function to determine if SAFER is active

No bug for this one. Robin noticed on my original commit to prevent
device switching with SAFER that I was probing the context directly
when there is a function to return the SAFER status that we should use
instead.

There turn out to be several other places where we were already doing
the same thing (I had copied the code from elsewhere...), so this commit
alters those to use the function instead.

Bug 707709: Fix overprinting not setting tags.

When overprinting with tags, ensure that we set the tag plane
correctly.

PDF interpreter - fix type 5 halftones

Bug #707631 "Problems with PreserveHalftoneInfo"

The problem is not with pdfwrite preserving halftones, but with the PDF
interpreter executing type 5 halftones.

This commit is based on the patch supplied by Alex in the bug report;
unfortunately that simple fix, while it does resolve the crash, leads to
many regressions in the test suite. It also deliberately doesn't
address the fact that the return value from gs_sethalftone_prepare() was
unchecked in several places.

Here we adopt Alex's patch, add the checks on the return value from
gs_sethalftone_prepare, but also correctly set up the identity transfer
function initially. The regressions were caused by the fact that the
default implementation essentially assumed a transfer function existed
and could map colour values incorrectly if one didn't.

Bug 707688: Fix rendering issue with psdcmyk16.

The depth value in the device is a ushort. The pdf14 code was
stashing it, and then restoring it later, but only using a byte.
16 spots * 16 bits requires a depth of 256, which doesn't fit
in a byte, hence 'bad things'.

The fix is simply to stash it in a ushort to match the device.

PostScript startup code - Fix some missing newlines

Bug #707680 "missing newline character in "Last OS error" error message"

Commit baa1d0bbff203e2f22eac91925a52e0ce4d17b74 replaced the use of the
'=' PostScript function with the internal '=only' operator, because the
language defined function can be overridden by PostScript and could be
abused.

However, the two are not quite identical, the default implementation of
'=' includes a newline, whereas '=only' does not. This left a couple of
places failing to emit a newline.

pxlcolor - emit zero sized clip rectangles

Bug #707687 "pxlcolor device fails to clip content"

Commit 4df181c0f8323b84239cb46535494835931994b4 adds clipping to the
xpswrite device, and also dropped empty (singlusar) clip rectangles.

It seems that doing this causes the vector device to draw images that
should be clipped out, because the emoty clip is not written to the
file. This only seems to cause a problem with the pxlcolor device,
possibly because other high level devices don't rely on the vector
device to do this work.

The simple solution is to write out the empty clip paths as we did
before.

Bug 707667: Handle TTF with only platform 0 cmap tables

PDF requires embedded TrueType fonts to use the 3,1 (Windows Unicode), 3,0
(Windows Symbol) or 1,0 (Macintosh) cmap table.

The font in this files contains only one cmap table, and it is a 0,1 (Unicode
1.1 semantics - deprecated) cmap.

Technically invalid, but other consumers accept it.

Since it is Unicode, treat it the same as the 3,1 cmap (may not work as expected
in all cases).

pdfwrite - avoid an error rendering a shading to an image

Following on from commit e57b1ffd95e189fedc68b2e235967dec649c20c3 which
corrected error handling when the image converter setup fails.

We'd prefer not to get an error at all, because that flags worrying
messages to the user. So here, if sx or sy are less than zero, which I
think indicates the shading is off the media, simply ignore the shading
altogether.

pdfwrite - properly handle error condition with shading rendering

No bug report, this is from a file supplied by a customer. The PDF file
has numerous (> 2500) shadings, defined in CMYK space which are
degenerate but drawn radically off the media. When run through pdfwrite
with ColorConversionStrategy=/RGB this crashes.

The reason is that the masked image converter which is used to render the
shadings into an image doesn't like the fact that the content is
entirely off the media and returns an error. The pdfwrite code spots
the error, but there's a logic mistake in the flow of control which
tries to remove the masked image converter, which is not possible
because we failed to install it, and leads to a crash.

This commit fixes the flow of control so that if we get an error
installing the converter, we don't try and remove it.
